{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492273"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1028"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1028"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.08,0.77,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80761"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1028"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80761"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a ten-month history of tiredness, palpitations, sweating, and weight loss. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears thin. Her pulse rate is 112/min and regular, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. The thyroid gland shows smooth, non-tender enlargement of both lobes with an overlying bruit. Thyroid function tests show TSH 0.1 mIU/L (0.5-5.0) and free thyroxine 23 pmol/L (12-22).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hashimoto thyroiditis","Toxic adenoma","Toxic multinodular goitre","Graves disease","Thyroid carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of hyperthyroidism including weight loss, palpitations, sweating and tachycardia. The presence of a diffuse, smooth goitre with an overlying bruit strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003EGraves disease\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism. The biochemistry showing suppressed TSH and elevated free thyroxine confirms thyrotoxicosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a transient thyrotoxic phase, but this typically only lasts 1-3 months, not the ten months described here. Additionally, thyroiditis does not cause a thyroid bruit, which is characteristic of the hypervascular state in Graves disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Etoxic multinodular goitre\u003C/strong\u003E typically present with irregular or nodular thyroid enlargement rather than the smooth, diffuse enlargement described. These conditions are also more common in older patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a thyroid nodule and rarely causes thyrotoxicosis. It would be unlikely to present with diffuse thyroid enlargement or systemic symptoms of thyroid hormone excess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe duration of symptoms (\u0026gt;3 months), presence of a thyroid bruit, and diffuse thyroid enlargement are key distinguishing features pointing to Graves disease in this case. If there is diagnostic uncertainty, a thyroid uptake scan can be helpful, as Graves disease shows diffusely increased uptake while thyroiditis shows decreased uptake.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Graves disease classically presents with diffuse, smooth thyroid enlargement and a thyroid bruit on examination","The combination of hyperthyroid symptoms, lid lag, and biochemical thyrotoxicosis for \u003E3 months duration suggests Graves disease rather than thyroiditis","A thyroid scan can help differentiate Graves disease (high uptake) from thyroiditis (low uptake) in unclear cases"],"references":["De Leo S, Lee S, Braverman L. Hyperthyroidism. The Lancet. 2016;388(10047):906-918. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(23)02016-0/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66073"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1028"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66073"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T20:27:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T20:27:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1028"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80761"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":